\q1 And any wickedness but the wickedness of a woman;
\q1
\v 14 Any calamity, but a calamity from those who hate me;
\q1 And any vengeance, but the vengeance of enemies.
\q1
\v 15 There is no head above the head of a serpent;
\q1 And there is no wrath above the wrath of an enemy.
\b
\q1
\v 16 I will rather dwell with a lion and a dragon,
\q1 Than keep house with a wicked woman.
\q1
\v 17 The wickedness of a woman changes her look,
\q1 And darkens her countenance as a bear does.
\q1
\v 18 Her husband will sit at meat among his neighbors,
\q1 And when he hears it he sighs bitterly.
\q1
\v 19 All malice is but little to the malice of a woman:
\q1 Let the portion of a sinner fall on her.
\q1
\v 20 \add As \add* the going up a sandy way \add is \add* to the feet of the aged,
\q1 So is a wife full of words to a quiet man.
\q1
\v 21 Throw not yourself upon the beauty of a woman;
\q1 And desire not a woman for her beauty.
\q1
\v 22 There is anger, and impudence, and great reproach,
\q1 If a woman maintain her husband.
\q1
\v 23 A wicked woman is abasement of heart,
\q1 And sadness of countenance, and a wounded heart:
\q1 A woman that will not make her husband happy
\q1 Is \add as \add* hands that hang down, and palsied knees.
\q1
\v 24 From a woman \add was \add* the beginning of sin;
\q1 And because of her we all die.
